Section 9 of the Arbitration and Conciliation Act, 1996, deals with interim measures by a court. It states that a party may, before or during arbitral proceedings or at any time after the making of the award but before it is enforced, apply to a court for an interim measure of protection. 

The court may grant the following interim measures:
- to preserve the subject-matter of the dispute;
- to take interim custody of the subject-matter of the dispute or to take steps to preserve evidence;
- to provide for the sale of perishable goods;
- to secure the amount in dispute;
- to restrain a party from transferring, alienating, or disposing of assets;
- to restrain a party from changing the position regarding the subject-matter of the dispute.

(Section 9, Arbitration and Conciliation Act, 1996)

Section 17 of the Registration Act, 1908, states that certain documents must be registered. It reads: 

"Section 17. Documents of which registration is compulsory. - (1) The following documents shall be registered, namely:-

(a) instruments of gift of immovable property;
(b) other non-testamentary instruments which purport or operate to create, declare, assign, limit or extinguish, whether in present or in future, any right, title or interest in immovable property;
(c) non-testamentary instruments which acknowledge the receipt or payment of any consideration on account of the creation, declaration, assignment, limitation or extinction of any such right, title or interest; and
(d) leases of immovable property from year to year, or for any term exceeding one year, or reserving a yearly rent;

(e) non-testamentary instruments transferring or assigning any decree or order of a Court or any award when such decree or order or award provides for the payment of any money or any other property, or for the delivery of any property, movable or immovable, and is not a will."

This section essentially mandates the registration of certain documents related to immovable property to ensure their validity and enforceability.

Yes, the Indian Evidence Act, 1872 has been amended to include provisions related to electronic evidence. 

Section 65A and 65B of the Indian Evidence Act, 1872 deal with the admissibility of electronic records and the conditions for their admissibility. 

Section 65B(1) states that any information contained in an electronic record which is printed on a paper, stored, recorded or copied in optical or magnetic media produced by a computer shall be deemed to be a document only if the conditions mentioned in Section 65B(2) are satisfied.

Section 65B(2) lists the conditions for admissibility of electronic records, which include:
- The electronic record was produced by the computer during the period over which the same was regularly used to store or process information for the purpose of any activity regularly carried on over that period by the person having lawful control over the use of that computer;
- During the said period, information of the kind contained in the electronic record was regularly fed into the computer in the ordinary course of the said activity;
- Throughout the material part of the said period, the computer was operating properly, or if not, then in respect of any period in which it was not operating properly, or was out of operation during that part of that period, the electronic record was produced during a period in which the computer was operating properly;
- The information contained in the electronic record reproduces or is derived from such information fed into the computer in the ordinary course of the said activity.

These provisions were introduced by the Information Technology Act, 2000 (No. 21 of 2000), which amended the Indian Evidence Act, 1872.

In a murder trial under Indian law, the prosecution must prove the following essential elements beyond reasonable doubt:

1. The death of the victim (Section 299 of the Indian Penal Code, 1860 (IPC));
2. The act of the accused caused the death (Section 299 IPC);
3. The act was done with the intention of causing death or with the knowledge that it was likely to cause death (Section 299 IPC);
4. The absence of any exception or justification for the act, such as self-defense (Chapter IV, IPC).

The prosecution must also prove the guilt of the accused under Section 302 IPC, which states that whoever commits murder shall be punished with death or imprisonment for life, or with imprisonment for a term which shall not be less than seven years but which may extend to imprisonment for life, and shall also be liable to fine.

The burden of proof lies on the prosecution to establish the guilt of the accused beyond reasonable doubt, as stated in Section 101 of the Indian Evidence Act, 1872.
